## 1. Derivation of $p(c_i \mid y_i,\mu)$

We first derive the conditional posterior distribution of the cluster assignment $c_i$.

By Bayes’ theorem,

$$
p(c_i = k \mid y_i,\mu)
\propto
p(c_i = k)\,p(y_i \mid c_i = k,\mu)
$$

since the normalizing constant does not depend on $k$. \### Prior for $c_i$

Because

$$
c_i \sim \text{Categorical}\left(\frac1K,\dots,\frac1K\right),
$$

we have

$$
p(c_i = k)=\frac1K.
$$

### Likelihood for $y_i$

From the model,

$$
y_i \mid c_i = k,\mu \sim N(\mu_k,1),
$$

so the likelihood is

$$
p(y_i \mid c_i = k,\mu)
=
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}
\exp\left(
-\frac12 (y_i-\mu_k)^2
\right).
$$

### Combine prior and likelihood

Thus,

$$
p(c_i = k \mid y_i,\mu)
\propto
\frac1K
\cdot
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}
\exp\left(
-\frac12 (y_i-\mu_k)^2
\right).
$$

Since $\frac1K$ and $\frac1{\sqrt{2\pi}}$ do not depend on $k$, they can be absorbed into the proportionality constant:

$$
p(c_i = k \mid y_i,\mu)
\propto
\exp\left(
-\frac12 (y_i-\mu_k)^2
\right).
$$

### Normalize

To obtain a valid categorical distribution, normalize over all $K$ components:

$$
p(c_i = k \mid y_i,\mu)
=
\frac{
\exp\left(
-\frac12 (y_i-\mu_k)^2
\right)
}{
\sum_{h=1}^{K}
\exp\left(
-\frac12 (y_i-\mu_h)^2
\right)
}.
$$

Therefore,

$$
c_i \mid y_i,\mu
\sim
\text{Categorical}(\pi_{i1},\dots,\pi_{iK})
$$

where

$$
\pi_{ik}
=
\frac{
\exp\left(
-\frac12 (y_i-\mu_k)^2
\right)
}{
\sum_{h=1}^{K}
\exp\left(
-\frac12 (y_i-\mu_h)^2
\right)
}.
$$

## 2. Derivation of $p(\mu_k \mid y,c)$

Next, we derive the conditional posterior for the component mean $\mu_k$.

By Bayes’ theorem,

$$
p(\mu_k \mid y,c)
\propto
p(\mu_k)\prod_{i:c_i=k} p(y_i \mid \mu_k).
$$

Only the observations assigned to cluster $k$ contribute to this conditional distribution.

### Prior for $\mu_k$

From the prior,

$$
\mu_k \sim N(0,\sigma^2),
$$

so

$$
p(\mu_k)
\propto
\exp\left(
-\frac{\mu_k^2}{2\sigma^2}
\right).
$$

### Likelihood for observations assigned to cluster $k$

For all observations with $c_i=k$,

$$
y_i \mid \mu_k \sim N(\mu_k,1),
$$

so

$$
p(y_i \mid \mu_k)
\propto
\exp\left(
-\frac12 (y_i-\mu_k)^2
\right).
$$

Thus,

$$
\prod_{i:c_i=k} p(y_i \mid \mu_k)
\propto
\exp\left(
-\frac12 \sum_{i:c_i=k}(y_i-\mu_k)^2
\right).
$$

### Combine prior and likelihood

Therefore,

$$
p(\mu_k \mid y,c)
\propto
\exp\left(
-\frac{\mu_k^2}{2\sigma^2}
\right)
\exp\left(
-\frac12 \sum_{i:c_i=k}(y_i-\mu_k)^2
\right).
$$

Combining the exponents:

$$
p(\mu_k \mid y,c)
\propto
\exp\left[
-\frac12
\left(
\frac{\mu_k^2}{\sigma^2}
+
\sum_{i:c_i=k}(y_i-\mu_k)^2
\right)
\right].
$$

### Expand the quadratic term

Define:

$$
n_k = \sum_{i=1}^{n} I(c_i=k),
$$

the number of observations in cluster $k$, and

$$
S_k = \sum_{i:c_i=k} y_i.
$$

Expand:

$$
\sum_{i:c_i=k}(y_i-\mu_k)^2
=
\sum_{i:c_i=k} y_i^2
-
2\mu_k S_k
+
n_k \mu_k^2.
$$

Substitute back:

$$
p(\mu_k \mid y,c)
\propto
\exp\left[
-\frac12
\left(
\frac{\mu_k^2}{\sigma^2}
+
\sum_{i:c_i=k} y_i^2
-
2\mu_k S_k
+
n_k\mu_k^2
\right)
\right].
$$

Since $\sum_{i:c_i=k} y_i^2$ does not depend on $\mu_k$, absorb it into the constant:

$$
p(\mu_k \mid y,c)
\propto
\exp\left[
-\frac12
\left(
\left(
n_k+\frac1{\sigma^2}
\right)\mu_k^2
-
2S_k\mu_k
\right)
\right].
$$

### Complete the square

Let

$$
A = n_k+\frac1{\sigma^2}.
$$

Then:

$$
A\mu_k^2 - 2S_k\mu_k
=
A\left(
\mu_k-\frac{S_k}{A}
\right)^2
-
A\left(
\frac{S_k}{A}
\right)^2.
$$

The second term does not depend on $\mu_k$, so it is absorbed into the constant.

Thus:

$$
p(\mu_k \mid y,c)
\propto
\exp\left[
-\frac{A}{2}
\left(
\mu_k-\frac{S_k}{A}
\right)^2
\right].
$$

This is the kernel of a normal distribution.

Therefore,

$$
\mu_k \mid y,c
\sim
N\left(
\frac{S_k}{A},
\frac1A
\right)
$$

that is,

$$
\mu_k \mid y,c
\sim
N\left(
\frac{\sum_{i:c_i=k} y_i}{n_k+1/\sigma^2},
\frac{1}{n_k+1/\sigma^2}
\right).
$$

## Problem 2: Variational inference derivations

Assume a mean‑field approximation. Derive a CAVI algorithm for the posterior distribution, $p(\mu, \textbf{x}|y)$. Show explicit derivations and resulting updates. Implement the algorithm in R. You may refer to [Blei, 2017](https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/01621459.2017.1285773) for details.

Your variational inference R function should

-   monitor convergence using the ELBO
-   return final estimates of the cluster assignments and means

We consider the Bayesian $K$-component Gaussian mixture model

$$
\mu_k \overset{iid}{\sim} N(0,\sigma^2), \quad k=1,\dots,K
$$

$$
c_i \overset{iid}{\sim} \text{Categorical}\left(\frac1K,\dots,\frac1K\right), \quad i=1,\dots,n
$$

$$
y_i \mid c_i=k,\mu \sim N(\mu_k,1), \quad i=1,\dots,n.
$$

We want to approximate the posterior distribution

$$
p(\mu,c\mid y).
$$

### Mean-field variational family

Assume the mean-field factorization

$$
q(\mu,c)=\prod_{k=1}^K q(\mu_k)\prod_{i=1}^n q(c_i),
$$

with

$$
q(\mu_k)=N(m_k,s_k^2)
$$

and

$$
q(c_i)=\text{Categorical}(\phi_{i1},\dots,\phi_{iK}),
\qquad
\sum_{k=1}^K \phi_{ik}=1.
$$

Here, $\phi_{ik}$ is the variational probability that observation $i$ belongs to cluster $k$.

Under coordinate ascent variational inference, each factor is updated according to

$$
\log q_j^*(z_j)=\mathbb E_{-j}[\log p(z_j,z_{-j},y)] + \text{const}.
$$

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 1. Derivation of $q(c_i)$

We first derive the optimal variational distribution for $c_i$.

Using the CAVI formula,

$$
\log q^*(c_i)
=
\mathbb E_{q(\mu)\,q(c_{-i})}\big[\log p(\mu,c,y)\big]+\text{const}.
$$

The joint distribution is

$$
p(\mu,c,y)=p(\mu)\,p(c)\,p(y\mid c,\mu).
$$

Among these terms, only $\log p(c_i)$ and $\log p(y_i\mid c_i,\mu)$ depend on $c_i$. Therefore,

$$
\log q^*(c_i=k)
=
\mathbb E\big[\log p(c_i=k)+\log p(y_i\mid c_i=k,\mu)\big]+\text{const}.
$$

Because

$$
p(c_i=k)=\frac1K,
$$

we have

$$
\log p(c_i=k)=\log\frac1K,
$$

which is constant across $k$, so it can be absorbed into the normalizing constant.

Also, since

$$
y_i\mid c_i=k,\mu \sim N(\mu_k,1),
$$

we have

$$
\log p(y_i\mid c_i=k,\mu)
=
-\frac12\log(2\pi)-\frac12(y_i-\mu_k)^2.
$$

Ignoring terms constant in $k$,

$$
\log q^*(c_i=k)
=
\mathbb E_{q(\mu_k)}
\left[
-\frac12(y_i-\mu_k)^2
\right]
+\text{const}.
$$

Expand the quadratic term:

$$
(y_i-\mu_k)^2
=
y_i^2-2y_i\mu_k+\mu_k^2.
$$

Thus,

$$
\mathbb E[(y_i-\mu_k)^2]
=
y_i^2-2y_i\mathbb E[\mu_k]+\mathbb E[\mu_k^2].
$$

Since $q(\mu_k)=N(m_k,s_k^2)$,

$$
\mathbb E[\mu_k]=m_k,
\qquad
\mathbb E[\mu_k^2]=m_k^2+s_k^2.
$$

Substituting gives

$$
\log q^*(c_i=k)
=
-\frac12\left(y_i^2-2y_i m_k+m_k^2+s_k^2\right)+\text{const}.
$$

Dropping the term $y_i^2$, which does not depend on $k$, we obtain

$$
\log q^*(c_i=k)
=
y_i m_k-\frac12(m_k^2+s_k^2)+\text{const}.
$$

Exponentiating both sides,

$$
q(c_i=k)\propto
\exp\left(
y_i m_k-\frac12(m_k^2+s_k^2)
\right).
$$

Therefore, the variational responsibilities are

$$
\phi_{ik}
=
\frac{
\exp\left(
y_i m_k-\frac12(m_k^2+s_k^2)
\right)
}{
\sum_{h=1}^K
\exp\left(
y_i m_h-\frac12(m_h^2+s_h^2)
\right)
}
$$

and

$$
q(c_i)=\text{Categorical}(\phi_{i1},\dots,\phi_{iK}).
$$

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 2. Derivation of $q(\mu_k)$

Next, we derive the optimal variational distribution for $\mu_k$.

Using the CAVI formula,

$$
\log q^*(\mu_k)
=
\mathbb E_{q(c)\,q(\mu_{-k})}[\log p(\mu,c,y)] + \text{const}.
$$

Only the prior term for $\mu_k$ and the likelihood terms involving $\mu_k$ are relevant. Hence,

$$
\log q^*(\mu_k)
=
\log p(\mu_k)
+
\sum_{i=1}^n \mathbb E_{q(c_i)}[\log p(y_i\mid c_i,\mu)]
+\text{const}.
$$

Since $y_i$ depends on $\mu_k$ only when $c_i=k$,

$$
\log q^*(\mu_k)
=
\log p(\mu_k)
+
\sum_{i=1}^n \phi_{ik}\log p(y_i\mid c_i=k,\mu_k)
+\text{const}.
$$

From the prior,

$$
\mu_k\sim N(0,\sigma^2),
$$

so

$$
\log p(\mu_k)
=
-\frac12\log(2\pi\sigma^2)-\frac{\mu_k^2}{2\sigma^2}.
$$

Ignoring constants,

$$
\log p(\mu_k)
=
-\frac{\mu_k^2}{2\sigma^2}+\text{const}.
$$

Also, from the likelihood,

$$
\log p(y_i\mid c_i=k,\mu_k)
=
-\frac12\log(2\pi)-\frac12(y_i-\mu_k)^2.
$$

Ignoring constants again,

$$
\log p(y_i\mid c_i=k,\mu_k)
=
-\frac12(y_i-\mu_k)^2+\text{const}.
$$

Therefore,

$$
\log q^*(\mu_k)
=
-\frac{\mu_k^2}{2\sigma^2}
-\frac12\sum_{i=1}^n \phi_{ik}(y_i-\mu_k)^2
+\text{const}.
$$

Expand the square:

$$
(y_i-\mu_k)^2
=
y_i^2-2y_i\mu_k+\mu_k^2.
$$

Substituting,

$$
\log q^*(\mu_k)
=
-\frac{\mu_k^2}{2\sigma^2}
-\frac12\sum_{i=1}^n \phi_{ik}y_i^2
+
\sum_{i=1}^n \phi_{ik}y_i\mu_k
-\frac12\sum_{i=1}^n \phi_{ik}\mu_k^2
+\text{const}.
$$

Collecting the terms involving $\mu_k$,

$$
\log q^*(\mu_k)
=
-\frac12
\left(
\frac1{\sigma^2}+\sum_{i=1}^n \phi_{ik}
\right)\mu_k^2
+
\left(
\sum_{i=1}^n \phi_{ik}y_i
\right)\mu_k
+\text{const}.
$$

This is the kernel of a Gaussian distribution. Therefore,

$$
q(\mu_k)=N(m_k,s_k^2),
$$

with

$$
s_k^2
=
\left(
\frac1{\sigma^2}+\sum_{i=1}^n \phi_{ik}
\right)^{-1}
$$

and

$$
m_k
=
s_k^2\sum_{i=1}^n \phi_{ik}y_i.
$$

So the optimal variational factor is

$$
q(\mu_k)
=
N\left(
s_k^2\sum_{i=1}^n \phi_{ik}y_i,\;
\left(\frac1{\sigma^2}+\sum_{i=1}^n \phi_{ik}\right)^{-1}
\right).
$$

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 3. ELBO

The evidence lower bound is

$$
\mathcal L(q)
=
\mathbb E_q[\log p(\mu,c,y)]
-
\mathbb E_q[\log q(\mu,c)].
$$

Using the factorization of the model,

$$
\mathcal L(q)
=
\mathbb E_q[\log p(\mu)]
+\mathbb E_q[\log p(c)]
+\mathbb E_q[\log p(y\mid c,\mu)]
-\mathbb E_q[\log q(\mu)]
-\mathbb E_q[\log q(c)].
$$

Each term can be computed explicitly.

First,

$$
\mathbb E_q[\log p(\mu)]
=
\sum_{k=1}^K
\left[
-\frac12\log(2\pi\sigma^2)
-\frac{m_k^2+s_k^2}{2\sigma^2}
\right].
$$

Second, since $p(c_i=k)=1/K$,

$$
\mathbb E_q[\log p(c)]
=
\sum_{i=1}^n\sum_{k=1}^K \phi_{ik}\log\frac1K
=
-n\log K.
$$

Third,

$$
\mathbb E_q[\log p(y\mid c,\mu)]
=
\sum_{i=1}^n\sum_{k=1}^K
\phi_{ik}
\left[
-\frac12\log(2\pi)
-\frac12\mathbb E_q[(y_i-\mu_k)^2]
\right].
$$

Since

$$
\mathbb E_q[(y_i-\mu_k)^2]=(y_i-m_k)^2+s_k^2,
$$

this becomes

$$
\mathbb E_q[\log p(y\mid c,\mu)]
=
\sum_{i=1}^n\sum_{k=1}^K
\phi_{ik}
\left[
-\frac12\log(2\pi)
-\frac12\big((y_i-m_k)^2+s_k^2\big)
\right].
$$

Fourth, for $q(\mu_k)=N(m_k,s_k^2)$, the entropy term is

$$
-\mathbb E_q[\log q(\mu)]
=
\sum_{k=1}^K \frac12\log(2\pi e s_k^2).
$$

Finally, for the categorical factors,

$$
-\mathbb E_q[\log q(c)]
=
-\sum_{i=1}^n\sum_{k=1}^K \phi_{ik}\log\phi_{ik}.
$$

Therefore, the full ELBO is

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal L
=&\;
\sum_{k=1}^K
\left[
-\frac12\log(2\pi\sigma^2)
-\frac{m_k^2+s_k^2}{2\sigma^2}
\right]
-n\log K \\
&+
\sum_{i=1}^n\sum_{k=1}^K
\phi_{ik}
\left[
-\frac12\log(2\pi)
-\frac12\big((y_i-m_k)^2+s_k^2\big)
\right] \\
&+
\sum_{k=1}^K \frac12\log(2\pi e s_k^2)
-\sum_{i=1}^n\sum_{k=1}^K \phi_{ik}\log\phi_{ik}.
\end{aligned}
$$

This ELBO can be used to monitor convergence of the CAVI algorithm.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 4. Resulting CAVI Algorithm

The coordinate ascent variational inference algorithm alternates between the following two updates.

### Update the cluster assignment probabilities

For each $i=1,\dots,n$,

$$
\phi_{ik}
=
\frac{
\exp\left(
y_i m_k-\frac12(m_k^2+s_k^2)
\right)
}{
\sum_{h=1}^K
\exp\left(
y_i m_h-\frac12(m_h^2+s_h^2)
\right)
}.
$$

### Update the variational distribution of $\mu_k$

For each $k=1,\dots,K$,

$$
s_k^2
=
\left(
\frac1{\sigma^2}+\sum_{i=1}^n \phi_{ik}
\right)^{-1}
$$

$$
m_k
=
s_k^2\sum_{i=1}^n \phi_{ik}y_i.
$$

### Convergence monitoring

At each iteration, compute the ELBO and stop when the increase in ELBO is smaller than a pre-specified tolerance.

### Final estimates

The final estimate of the cluster assignment is

$$
\hat c_i=\arg\max_k \phi_{ik},
$$

and the final estimate of the component means is

$$
\hat\mu_k=m_k.
$$

