### Discussion

Both the Gibbs sampler and variational Bayes identified a clear two-cluster structure in the Old Faithful waiting time data. The estimated component means from the two approaches were similar, suggesting that the variational approximation captured the main posterior location reasonably well.

Variational Bayes was substantially faster than Gibbs sampling because it uses deterministic coordinate updates instead of posterior sampling. However, Gibbs sampling provides full posterior draws and therefore allows uncertainty quantification and convergence diagnostics. The trace plots from three chains suggested reasonable mixing after burn-in, and the effective sample sizes were adequate for the component means. Overall, VB provided a fast approximation, while Gibbs sampling gave richer inferential output.

